{"title_page": "Shane Ellis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Shane Ellis\n| image = \n| fullname = Shane Ellis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|9|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = St God of John Hospital Murdoch\n| death_date = 19 April 2020\n| death_place = Leeming Senior High School\n| height = 188 cm\n| weight = 86 kg\n| draftpick = No. 38, [[1988 VFL draft|1989 pre-season draft]]<!--do not capitalise draft or pre-season draft per 1988 AFL draft article title and the Wikipedia manual of style-->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1991\n| repstatsend = 1986\n| years1 = 1980\u20131991\n| club1 = [[East Fremantle Football Club|East Fremantle]]\n| games_goals1 = 204\n| years2 = 1989\n| club2 = [[West Coast Eagles|West Coast]]\n| games_goals2 = 10 (8)\n| sooyears1 = 1982\u20131986\n| sooteam1 = [[Western Australia Australian rules football team|Western Australia]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 5\n| careerhighlights = \n}}\n\n'''Shane Ellis''' (born 27 September 1960) is a former [[Australian rules football]]er who played with the [[West Coast Eagles]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] (VFL) and [[East Fremantle Football Club|East Fremantle]] in the [[West Australian Football League]] (WAFL).\n\nEllis won East Fremantle's 'Fairest and Best' award in 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australianfootball.com/players/player/Shane%2BEllis/12673| title=Shane Ellis - Player Bio| publisher=Australian Football|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> and twice played in losing Grand Finals with the WAFL club, in 1984 and 1986. The year in between, Ellis had spent with [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] but hadn't been able to break into the seniors.\n\nA half back, he got another opportunity to play in the VFL when he was signed by West Coast. He appeared in the first six games for the [[1989 VFL season]], during which time he kicked three goals in a game against [[Sydney Swans|Sydney]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/S/Shane_Ellis.html| title=Shane Ellis| publisher=AFL Tables}}</ref> Ellis played four further games that year and finished his career back at East Fremantle where he brought up his 200th game before retiring in 1991. He represented Western Australia at [[Interstate matches in Australian rules football|interstate football]] on five occasions between 1982 and 1986.\n\nEllis, who resides in Perth W.A, is now a sports teacher at Leeming Senior High School where he has worked for many years.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1983 Western Australia State of Origin players}}\n{{1986 Western Australia State of Origin players}}\n{{1989 VFL pre-season draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, Shane}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:West Coast Eagles players]]\n[[Category:East Fremantle Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Shane Ellis\n| image = \n| fullname = Shane Ellis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|9|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 188 cm\n| weight = 86 kg\n| draftpick = No. 38, [[1988 VFL draft|1989 pre-season draft]]<!--do not capitalise draft or pre-season draft per 1988 AFL draft article title and the Wikipedia manual of style-->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1991\n| repstatsend = 1986\n| years1 = 1980\u20131991\n| club1 = [[East Fremantle Football Club|East Fremantle]]\n| games_goals1 = 204\n| years2 = 1989\n| club2 = [[West Coast Eagles|West Coast]]\n| games_goals2 = 10 (8)\n| sooyears1 = 1982\u20131986\n| sooteam1 = [[Western Australia Australian rules football team|Western Australia]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 5\n| careerhighlights = \n}}\n\n'''Shane Ellis''' (born 27 September 1960) is a former [[Australian rules football]]er who played with the [[West Coast Eagles]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] (VFL) and [[East Fremantle Football Club|East Fremantle]] in the [[West Australian Football League]] (WAFL).\n\nEllis won East Fremantle's 'Fairest and Best' award in 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australianfootball.com/players/player/Shane%2BEllis/12673| title=Shane Ellis - Player Bio| publisher=Australian Football|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> and twice played in losing Grand Finals with the WAFL club, in 1984 and 1986. The year in between, Ellis had spent with [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] but hadn't been able to break into the seniors.\n\nA half back, he got another opportunity to play in the VFL when he was signed by West Coast. He appeared in the first six games for the [[1989 VFL season]], during which time he kicked three goals in a game against [[Sydney Swans|Sydney]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/S/Shane_Ellis.html| title=Shane Ellis| publisher=AFL Tables}}</ref> Ellis played four further games that year and finished his career back at East Fremantle where he brought up his 200th game before retiring in 1991. He represented Western Australia at [[Interstate matches in Australian rules football|interstate football]] on five occasions between 1982 and 1986.\n\nEllis, who resides in Perth W.A, is now a sports teacher at Leeming Senior High School where he has worked for many years.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1983 Western Australia State of Origin players}}\n{{1986 Western Australia State of Origin players}}\n{{1989 VFL pre-season draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, Shane}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:West Coast Eagles players]]\n[[Category:East Fremantle Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "124.177.205.138", "label": "unsafe", "comment": ""